defs.docs:
This crate contains parser combinators, roughly based on the Haskell library
 [parsec](http://hackage.haskell.org/package/parsec).

defs.name: primitives
defs.docs:
Module containing the primitive types which is used to create and compose more advanced
 parsers.

defs.name: SourcePosition
defs.docs: Struct which represents a position in a source file.

defs.name: line
defs.docs: Current line of the input

defs.name: column
defs.docs: Current column of the input

defs.name: BytePosition
defs.docs: Struct which represents a position in a byte stream.

defs.name: position
defs.docs: Current position

defs.name: Info
defs.docs:
Enum holding error information. Variants are defined for `Stream::Item` and `Stream::Range` as
 well as string variants holding simple descriptions.

defs.name: map_token
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Info<U, R>

defs.name: map_range
defs.value: fn <F, S> (self, f: F) -> Info<T, S>

defs.name: Unexpected
defs.docs: Error indicating an unexpected token has been encountered in the stream

defs.name: Expected
defs.docs: Error indicating that the parser expected something else

defs.name: Message
defs.docs: Generic message

defs.name: Other
defs.docs: Variant for containing other types of errors

defs.name: Error
defs.docs: Enum used to store information about an error that has occurred during parsing.

defs.name: map_token
defs.value: fn <F, U> (self, f: F) -> Error<U, R>

defs.name: map_range
defs.value: fn <F, S> (self, f: F) -> Error<T, S>

defs.name: end_of_input
defs.docs: Returns the `end_of_input` error.

defs.name: fmt_errors
defs.docs: Formats a slice of errors in a human readable way.

defs.name: Consumed
defs.docs: Constructor indicating that the parser has consumed elements

defs.name: Empty
defs.docs: Constructor indicating that the parser did not consume any elements

defs.name: Consumed
defs.docs: Enum used to indicate if a parser consumed any items of the stream it was given as an input.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Returns true if `self` is empty.

defs.name: into_inner
defs.docs: Extracts the contained value.

defs.name: as_consumed
defs.docs: Converts `self` into the `Consumed` state.

defs.name: into_consumed
defs.docs: Converts `self` into the `Consumed` state.

defs.name: as_empty
defs.docs: Converts `self` into the `Empty` state.

defs.name: into_empty
defs.docs: Converts `self` into the `Empty` state.

defs.name: map
defs.docs: Maps over the contained value without changing the consumed state.

defs.name: combine
defs.value: fn <F, U, I> (self, f: F) -> ParseResult<U, I>
defs.docs: Combines the `Consumed` flags from `self` and the result of `f`.

defs.name: combine_consumed
defs.value: fn <F, U, I> (self, f: F) -> ConsumedResult<U, I>

defs.name: ParseError
defs.docs:
Struct which hold information about an error that occurred at a specific position.
 Can hold multiple instances of `Error` if more that one error occurred in the same position.

defs.name: position
defs.docs: The position where the error occurred

defs.name: errors
defs.docs:
A vector containing specific information on what errors occurred at `position`. Usually
 a fully formed message contains one `Unexpected` error and one or more `Expected` errors.
 `Message` and `Other` may also appear (`combine` never generates these errors on its own)
 and may warrant custom handling.

defs.name: new
defs.value: fn (position: S::Position, error: Error<S::Item, S::Range>) -> ParseError<S>
defs.docs: Constructs a new `ParseError` which occurred at `position`.

defs.name: empty
defs.docs: Constructs an error with no other information than the position it occurred at.

defs.name: from_errors
defs.value: fn (position: S::Position, errors: Vec<Error<S::Item, S::Range>>) -> ParseError<S>
defs.docs: Constructs a `ParseError` with multiple causes.

defs.name: end_of_input
defs.docs:
Constructs an end of input error. Should be returned by parsers which encounter end of
 input unexpectedly.

defs.name: add_message
defs.docs: Adds a `Message` error, taking care not to add duplicated errors.

defs.name: add_error
defs.docs:
Adds an error if `error` does not exist in this `ParseError` already (as determined byte
 `PartialEq`).

defs.name: set_expected
defs.docs: Remvoes all `Expected` errors in `self` and adds `info` instead.

defs.name: merge
defs.docs:
Merges two `ParseError`s. If they exist at the same position the errors of `other` are
 added to `self` (using `add_error` to skip duplicates). If they are not at the same
 position the error furthest ahead are returned, ignoring the other `ParseError`.

defs.name: translate_position
defs.value: fn (mut self, initial_string: &'s str) -> ParseError<&'s str>
defs.docs: Converts the pointer-based position into an indexed position.

defs.name: translate_position
defs.docs: Converts the pointer-based position into an indexed position.

defs.name: State
defs.docs:
The `State<I>` struct keeps track of the current position in the stream `I` using the
 `Positioner` trait to update the position.

defs.name: position
defs.docs: The current position

defs.name: input
defs.docs: The input stream used when items are requested

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Creates a new `State<I>` from an input stream. Initializes the position to
 `Positioner::start()`.

defs.name: ParseResult
defs.docs:
A type alias over the specific `Result` type used by parsers to indicate wether they were
 successful or not.
 `O` is the type that is output on success.
 `I` is the specific stream type used in the parser.

defs.name: StreamOnce
defs.docs: `StreamOnce` represents a sequence of items that can be extracted one by one.

defs.name: Item
defs.docs: The type of items which is yielded from this stream.

defs.name: Range
defs.docs:
The type of a range of items yielded from this stream.
 Types which do not a have a way of yielding ranges of items should just use the
 `Self::Item` for this type.

defs.name: Position
defs.docs:
Type which represents the position in a stream.
 `Ord` is required to allow parsers to determine which of two positions are further ahead.

defs.name: uncons
defs.docs:
Takes a stream and removes its first item, yielding the item and the rest of the elements.
 Returns `Err` if no element could be retrieved.

defs.name: position
defs.docs: Returns the current position of the stream.

defs.name: Stream
defs.docs: A stream of tokens which can be duplicated

defs.name: RangeStream
defs.docs: A `RangeStream` is an extension of `Stream` which allows for zero copy parsing.

defs.name: uncons_range
defs.value: fn (&mut self, size: usize) -> Result<Self::Range, Error<Self::Item, Self::Range>>
defs.docs:
Takes `size` elements from the stream.
 Fails if the length of the stream is less than `size`.

defs.name: uncons_while
defs.value: fn <F> (&mut self, f: F) -> Result<Self::Range, Error<Self::Item, Self::Range>>
defs.docs:
Takes items from stream, testing each one with `predicate`.
 returns the range of items which passed `predicate`.

defs.name: FullRangeStream
defs.docs: A `RangeStream` which is capable of providing it's entire range.

defs.name: range
defs.docs: Returns the entire range of `self`

defs.name: uncons_while
defs.value: fn <I, F> (mut input: I, predicate: F) -> ConsumedResult<I::Range, I>
defs.docs: Removes items from the input while `predicate` returns `true`.

defs.name: len
defs.docs:
Returns the remaining length of `self`.
 The returned length need not be the same as the number of items left in the stream.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Returns `true` if the range does not contain any elements (`Range::len() == 0`)

defs.name: SliceStream
defs.docs: Newtype for constructing a stream from a slice where the items in the slice are not copyable.

defs.name: IteratorStream
defs.docs:
Wrapper around iterators which allows them to be treated as a stream.
 Returned by [`from_iter`].

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Converts an `Iterator` into a stream.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Creates a `StreamOnce` instance from a value implementing `std::io::Read`.

defs.name: Positioner
defs.docs: Trait for updating the position for types which can be yielded from a `Stream`.

defs.name: Position
defs.docs: The type which keeps track of the position.

defs.name: start
defs.docs: Creates a start position

defs.name: update
defs.docs: Updates the position given that `self` has been taken from the stream

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <F, T2> (self, f: F) -> ConsumedResult<F::Output, E>

defs.name: ConsumedResult
defs.docs:
A `Result` type which has the consumed status flattened into the result.
 Conversions to and from `std::result::Result` can be done using `result.into()` or
 `From::from(result)`

defs.name: Parser
defs.docs:
By implementing the `Parser` trait a type says that it can be used to parse an input stream
 into the type `Output`.

defs.name: Input
defs.docs:
The type which is taken as input for the parser. The type must implement the `Stream` trait
 which allows the parser to read items from the type.

defs.name: Output
defs.docs: The type which is returned if the parser is successful.

defs.name: parse
defs.value: fn (&mut self, input: Self::Input) -> Result<(Self::Output, Self::Input), ParseError<Self::Input>>
defs.docs: Entry point of the parser. Takes some input and tries to parse it.

defs.name: parse_stream
defs.value: fn (&mut self, input: Self::Input) -> ParseResult<Self::Output, Self::Input>
defs.docs: Parses using the stream `input` by calling [`Stream::uncons`] one or more times.

defs.name: parse_stream_consumed
defs.value: fn (&mut self, mut input: Self::Input) -> ConsumedResult<Self::Output, Self::Input>
defs.docs: Parses using the stream `input` by calling [`Stream::uncons`] one or more times.

defs.name: parse_lazy
defs.value: fn (&mut self, input: Self::Input) -> ConsumedResult<Self::Output, Self::Input>
defs.docs: Parses using the stream `input` by calling [`Stream::uncons`] one or more times.

defs.name: add_error
defs.docs:
Adds the first error that would normally be returned by this parser if it failed with an
 `EmptyErr` result.

defs.name: by_ref
defs.docs: Borrows a parser instead of consuming it.

defs.name: with
defs.docs:
Discards the value of the `self` parser and returns the value of `p`.
 Fails if any of the parsers fails.

defs.name: skip
defs.docs:
Discards the value of the `p` parser and returns the value of `self`.
 Fails if any of the parsers fails.

defs.name: and
defs.docs:
Parses with `self` followed by `p`.
 Succeeds if both parsers succeed, otherwise fails.
 Returns a tuple with both values on success.

defs.name: or
defs.docs:
Returns a parser which attempts to parse using `self`. If `self` fails without consuming
 any input it tries to consume the same input using `p`.

defs.name: then
defs.value: fn <N, F> (self, f: F) -> Then<Self, F>
defs.docs:
Parses using `self` and then passes the value to `f` which returns a parser used to parse
 the rest of the input.

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <F, B> (self, f: F) -> Map<Self, F>
defs.docs: Uses `f` to map over the parsed value.

defs.name: flat_map
defs.value: fn <F, B> (self, f: F) -> FlatMap<Self, F>
defs.docs: Uses `f` to map over the output of `self`. If `f` returns an error the parser fails.

defs.name: message
defs.docs: Parses with `self` and if it fails, adds the message `msg` to the error.

defs.name: expected
defs.docs:
Parses with `self` and if it fails without consuming any input any expected errors are
 replaced by `msg`. `msg` is then used in error messages as "Expected `msg`".

defs.name: and_then
defs.value: fn <F, O, E> (self, f: F) -> AndThen<Self, F>
defs.docs:
Parses with `self` and applies `f` on the result if `self` parses successfully.
 `f` may optionally fail with an error which is automatically converted to a `ParseError`.

defs.name: iter
defs.docs:
Creates an iterator from a parser and a state. Can be used as an alternative to [`many`] when
 collecting directly into a `FromIterator` type is not desirable.

defs.name: boxed
defs.docs:
Turns the parser into a trait object by putting it in a `Box`. Can be used to easily
 return parsers from functions without naming the type.

defs.name: BufferedStream
defs.docs: A `BufferedStream` wraps an instance `StreamOnce`, allowing it to be used as a `Stream`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs:
Constructs a new `BufferedStream` froma a `StreamOnce` instance with a `lookahead` number
 of elements stored in the buffer.

defs.name: combinator
defs.docs: Module containing all specific parsers.

defs.name: any
defs.docs: Parses any token.

defs.name: satisfy
defs.docs: Parses a token and succeeds depending on the result of `predicate`.

defs.name: satisfy_map
defs.value: fn <I, P, R> (predicate: P) -> SatisfyMap<I, P>
defs.docs:
Parses a token and passes it to `predicate`. If `predicate` returns `Some` the parser succeeds
 and returns the value inside the `Option`. If `predicate` returns `None` the parser fails
 without consuming any input.

defs.name: token
defs.docs: Parses a character and succeeds if the character is equal to `c`.

defs.name: tokens
defs.value: fn <C, T, I> (cmp: C, expected: Info<I::Item, I::Range>, tokens: T) -> Tokens<C, T, I>
defs.docs: Parses multiple tokens.

defs.name: position
defs.docs: Parser which just returns the current position in the stream.

defs.name: one_of
defs.docs: Extract one token and succeeds if it is part of `tokens`.

defs.name: none_of
defs.docs: Extract one token and succeeds if it is not part of `tokens`.

defs.name: count
defs.value: fn <F, P> (count: usize, parser: P) -> Count<F, P>
defs.docs: Parses `parser` from zero up to `count` times.

defs.name: skip_count
defs.docs: Parses `parser` from zero up to `count` times skipping the output of `parser`.

defs.name: count_min_max
defs.value: fn <F, P> (min: usize, max: usize, parser: P) -> CountMinMax<F, P>
defs.docs: Parses `parser` from `min` to `max` times (including `min` and `max`).

defs.name: skip_count_min_max
defs.value:
fn

(min: usize, max: usize, parser: P) -> self::skip_count_min_max::SkipCountMinMax
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` from `min` to `max` times (including `min` and `max`)
 skipping the output of `parser`.

defs.name: choice
defs.docs:
Takes an array of parsers and tries to apply them each in order.
 Fails if all the parsers fails or if an applied parser consumes input before failing.

defs.name: unexpected
defs.docs:
Always fails with `message` as an unexpected error.
 Never consumes any input.

defs.name: value
defs.docs: Always returns the value `v` without consuming any input.

defs.name: not_followed_by
defs.docs:
Succeeds only if `parser` fails.
 Never consumes any input.

defs.name: eof
defs.docs: Succeeds only if the stream is at end of input, fails otherwise.

defs.name: into_result
defs.docs:
Converts the iterator to a `ParseResult`, returning `Ok` if the parsing so far has be done
 without any errors which consumed data.

defs.name: many
defs.docs: Parses `p` zero or more times returning a collection with the values from `p`.

defs.name: skip_many
defs.docs: Parses `p` zero or more times ignoring the result.

defs.name: skip_many1
defs.docs: Parses `p` one or more times ignoring the result.

defs.name: many1
defs.docs: Parses `p` one or more times returning a collection with the values from `p`.

defs.name: sep_by
defs.value: fn <F, P, S> (parser: P, separator: S) -> SepBy<F, P, S>
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` zero or more time separated by `separator`, returning a collection with the
 values from `p`.

defs.name: sep_by1
defs.value: fn <F, P, S> (parser: P, separator: S) -> SepBy1<F, P, S>
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` one or more time separated by `separator`, returning a collection with the
 values from `p`.

defs.name: sep_end_by
defs.value: fn <F, P, S> (parser: P, separator: S) -> SepEndBy<F, P, S>
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` zero or more times separated and ended by `separator`, returning a collection
 with the values from `p`.

defs.name: sep_end_by1
defs.value: fn <F, P, S> (parser: P, separator: S) -> SepEndBy1<F, P, S>
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` one or more times separated and ended by `separator`, returning a collection
 with the values from `p`.

defs.name: parser
defs.value: fn <I, O, F> (f: F) -> FnParser<I, F>
defs.docs: Wraps a function, turning it into a parser.

defs.name: optional
defs.docs:
Parses `parser` and outputs `Some(value)` if it succeeds, `None` if it fails without
 consuming any input. Fails if `parser` fails after having consumed some input.

defs.name: between
defs.value: fn <I, L, R, P> (open: L, close: R, parser: P) -> Between<L, R, P>
defs.docs:
Parses `open` followed by `parser` followed by `close`.
 Returns the value of `parser`.

defs.name: chainl1
defs.value: fn <P, Op> (parser: P, op: Op) -> Chainl1<P, Op>
defs.docs:
Parses `p` 1 or more times separated by `op`. The value returned is the one produced by the
 left associative application of the function returned by the parser `op`.

defs.name: chainr1
defs.value: fn <P, Op> (parser: P, op: Op) -> Chainr1<P, Op>
defs.docs:
Parses `p` one or more times separated by `op`. The value returned is the one produced by the
 right associative application of the function returned by `op`.

defs.name: try
defs.docs:
`try(p)` behaves as `p` except it acts as if the parser hadn't consumed any input if `p` fails after
 consuming input.

defs.name: look_ahead
defs.docs: `look_ahead(p)` acts as `p` but doesn't consume input on success.

defs.name: with
defs.value: fn <P1, P2> (p1: P1, p2: P2) -> With<P1, P2>
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p1.with(p2)`].

defs.name: skip
defs.value: fn <P1, P2> (p1: P1, p2: P2) -> Skip<P1, P2>

defs.name: message
defs.value:
fn

(p: P, msg: Info<::Item, ::Range>) -> Message
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p1.message(msg)`].

defs.name: or
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p1.or(p2)`].

defs.name: map
defs.value: fn <P, F, B> (p: P, f: F) -> Map<P, F>
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p.map(f)`].

defs.name: flat_map
defs.value: fn <P, F, B> (p: P, f: F) -> FlatMap<P, F>
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p.flat_map(f)`].

defs.name: then
defs.value: fn <P, F, N> (p: P, f: F) -> Then<P, F>
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p.then(f)`].

defs.name: expected
defs.value:
fn

(p: P, info: Info<::Item, ::Range>) -> Expected
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p.expected(info)`].

defs.name: and_then
defs.value: fn <P, F, O, E> (p: P, f: F) -> AndThen<P, F>
defs.docs: Equivalent to [`p.and_then(f)`].

defs.name: env_parser
defs.value: fn <E, I, O> (env: E, parser: fn(E, I) -> ParseResult<O, I>) -> EnvParser<E, I, O>
defs.docs:
Constructs a parser out of an environment and a function which needs the given environment to
 do the parsing. This is commonly useful to allow multiple parsers to share some environment
 while still allowing the parsers to be written in separate functions.

defs.name: recognize
defs.docs:
Constructs a parser which returns the tokens parsed by `parser` accumulated in
 `F: FromIterator<P::Input::Item>` instead of `P::Output`.

defs.name: range
defs.docs: Module containing zero-copy parsers.

defs.name: range
defs.docs:
Zero-copy parser which reads a range of length `i.len()` and succeds if `i` is equal to that
 range.

defs.name: take
defs.docs: Zero-copy parser which reads a range of length `n`.

defs.name: take_while
defs.docs: Zero-copy parser which reads a range of 0 or more tokens which satisfy `f`.

defs.name: take_while1
defs.docs: Zero-copy parser which reads a range of 1 or more tokens which satisfy `f`.

defs.name: take_until_range
defs.docs: Zero-copy parser which reads a range of 0 or more tokens until `r` is found.

defs.name: byte
defs.docs: Module containing parsers specialized on byte streams.

defs.name: byte
defs.docs: Parses a byteacter and succeeds if the byteacter is equal to `c`.

defs.name: digit
defs.docs: Parses a base-10 digit (09).

defs.name: space
defs.docs: Parses a `b' '`, `b'\t'`, `b'\n'` or `'b\'r'`.

defs.name: spaces
defs.docs: Skips over [`space`] zero or more times

defs.name: newline
defs.docs: Parses a newline byteacter (`b'\n'`).

defs.name: crlf
defs.docs: Parses carriage return and newline (`&b"\r\n"`), returning the newline byteacter.

defs.name: tab
defs.docs: Parses a tab byteacter (`b'\t'`).

defs.name: upper
defs.docs: Parses an uppercase ASCII letter (AZ).

defs.name: lower
defs.docs: Parses an lowercase ASCII letter (az).

defs.name: alpha_num
defs.docs: Parses either an ASCII alphabet letter or digit (az, AZ, 09).

defs.name: letter
defs.docs: Parses an ASCII alphabet letter (az, AZ).

defs.name: oct_digit
defs.docs: Parses an octal digit.

defs.name: hex_digit
defs.docs: Parses an ASCII hexdecimal digit (accepts both uppercase and lowercase).

defs.name: bytes
defs.docs: Parses the bytes `s`.

defs.name: bytes_cmp
defs.value: fn <'a, C, I> (s: &'static [u8], cmp: C) -> BytesCmp<C, I>
defs.docs: Parses the bytes `s` using `cmp` to compare each token.

defs.name: num
defs.docs: Parsers for decoding numbers in big-endian or little-endian order.

defs.name: char
defs.docs: Module containing parsers specialized on character streams.

defs.name: char
defs.docs: Parses a character and succeeds if the character is equal to `c`.
